{
  "stem": "18102.2",
  "chunk_idx": 11,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 147.8,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 23,
      "text": "But then, an hour or so later, the Russian army started marching in from the other direction.",
      "word_count": 17
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 24,
      "text": "And it was a very happy occasion for the Bialystokers.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 25,
      "text": "They cheered the Russian army.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 26,
      "text": "Obviously, it was the lesser of two evils.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 27,
      "text": "And, and suddenly red flags showed up among some of the people.",
      "word_count": 12
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 28,
      "text": "There were probably a number of communists around, too, that applauded it from a political point of view as well.",
      "word_count": 20
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 29,
      "text": "But generally speaking, even the Jews were certainly less fearful of the Russians than they were of the Germans, with good reason, historic reasons.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 30,
      "text": "So there was a, a festive feeling among the Jewish population and the Polish population, and I watched as the Russian army marched in.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 31,
      "text": "Behind the Russian army came all of the people who had ran away, who had left Bialystok for fear of their lives.",
      "word_count": 22
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 27,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 32,
      "text": "The councilmen, other prominent citizens, and others who had left Bialystok now felt the safety of the Russian presence to come back to Bialystok, all except my father and one other, other friend of his who did not return, much to the disappointment, of course, to my mother and myself who expected that they would return with all the others.",
      "word_count": 60
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 28,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "My mother was, in fact, besides herself in worry that my father didn't return and perhaps something horrible had befallen him.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 28,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "What was his motivation of not returning?",
      "word_count": 7
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 28,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "Where was he?",
      "word_count": 3
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 28,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "The people that could tell her, the other friends that had returned, simply said that he was a very stubborn fool who wouldn't trust the Russians because he was a staunch anti-communist-- he had written extensively, as a Bundist, against communism-- and would not return with the Russian army, that they had argued with him.",
      "word_count": 55
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 29,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "They told him that it would be much safer for them.",
      "word_count": 11
    }
  ],
